{{disputed|date=July 2018}}
''''Abdullāh ibn 'Ibādh al-Tamimi''' ({{lang-ar|عبدالله بن اباض التميمي}}, d. 708) was a [[Tabi‘un|Tabi'i]], a jurist and one of the best students of [[Ibn Abbas]],{{fact|date=July 2018}} who narrated [[hadith]]s from [[Aisha]] and a large number of the [[Sahaba]] who witnessed the [[Battle of Badr]].{{fact|date=July 2018}} He and [[Jābir ibn Zayd]] were [[imam|imams]] in the [[tafsir]] and sciences of [[Hadith]].{{fact|date=July 2018}}

==Lineage==
{{unreferencedsect|date=July 2018}}
Abdullah ibn Ibadh belongs to the tribe of Bani Murra who are descendants of Murra ibn Ubayd ibn Tamim, and thus he belongs to the tribe of [[Bani Tamim]], one of the largest in the Arabian peninsula.

==Biography==
Ibn Ibadh grew up during the reign of [[Muawiyah I]], the first ruler of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], and died during the reign of [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]].<ref>[[Donald Hawley]], ''Oman'', pg. 199. Jubilee edition. [[Kensington]]: [[Stacey International]], 1995. {{ISBN|0905743636}}</ref>

The [[Ibadi]] school of thought is attributed to ibn Ibadh, although there is some recent research<ref>Hoffman, V. J. (2015) [https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/rec3.12164 Ibāḍism: History, Doctrines, and Recent Scholarship]. Religion Compass, 9: 297–307</ref> that qualifies this attribution.

